<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-298-197  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 298 197.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Jan 23 1989 v10 n4 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multiple-protocol spec set by Novell and Apple.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Greenstein, Irwin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Novell Inc released a specification that allows users to access upto 32 dissimilar protocols and 16 dissimilar adapters at the sametime on local area networks (LANs) of DOS and OS-2 computers.andO;Novell developed the Open Link Interface (OLI) specification withApple Computer Inc. OLI furnishes guidelines for hardware andsoftware vendors developing the interface between LAN adapters andLAN protocol stacks that will interoperate on DOS and OS-2platforms.andP;  Following the OLI spec will allow suppliers of LANadapter cards to put out a single interface board for a DOS- orOS-2-based computer that supports many different networkingprotocols.andP;  Customers with OLI-compliant products can then sharethe different networking services of differing protocols from asingle personal computer over a variety of wiring media.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Novell Inc. (product introduction)Apple Computer Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    NOVL; AAPL.andO;Product:   Open Link Interface (Computer network software) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     New ProductProtocolSpecifications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>